Diagnosis.
Males may be determined by the following character combination: galea strongly tessellate, dull; clypeus typically with inverted-T maculation, although upper half frequently weak or absent (
Fig. 51B
); supraclypeus with transverse, often somewhat amorphous, maculation; T2–T6 with well-defined apical appressed setal bands; T7 with slight medial longitudinal carina, lateral projections with tips relatively blunt and only slightly recurved posteriorly, medial projections long with tips rounded (
Fig. 61B
); S5 with dense, light erect setal patches (
Fig. 38B
); and S6 with transparent apical rim medially (
Fig. 38B
). Females may be determined with the following character combination: galea strongly tessellate, dull; clypeus typically with inverted-T maculation, although upper half may be weak or absent (
Fig. 41B
); supraclypeus with strong transverse maculation, filling most of area; terga shiny between punctures; T2–T4 typically with well-defined apical appressed setal bands, though some species with wider bands have almost no basal black zone; and anal fimbria dark brown, often partially obscured by light setae dorsally.

Male description.
Head: Facial maculations usually pale yellow, uncommonly richly yellow. Galea roughly reaching foretrochanter in repose, barely exceeding its front margin if at all; medium to dark brown; strongly tessellate, with weak reflections if any. Mandible with inferior tooth unusually expanded and broadly ovular, running about parallel to main blade; maculated from base to start or middle of inferior tooth (
Fig. 51B
). Labral rim tridentate. Clypeal maculation varying from band to inverted-T, very nearly reaching lateral sides, filling about half of clypeal height if not inverted-T (
Fig. 51B
); punctation moderately to weakly sparser within maculation than without. Paraocular area immaculate. Supraclypeal area maculated; usually transverse, sometimes amorphous. Scape maculated; fully along length and most of width below. Mesosoma: Scutum shiny; with impunctate areas, sometimes small or obscure due to invasion by sparse punctures. Tegula translucent to weakly transparent, medium to light brown. Basitibial plate weak but present; weakly outlined, often obscured by setae. Metasoma: T1 covered in appressed setae; T2–T6 with thinner apical appressed setal bands, not or very weakly undulate. Terga moderately to weakly tessellate between punctures, with relatively weak reflections; apparent through appressed setae only where sparse. Tergal rims transparent, slightly tan to clear. Male T7 (
Fig. 61B
) with very weak medial longitudinal carina, sometimes only distinct near base of carina; lateral projections somewhat recurved, wide flanges; medial projections long and apically rounded, sides of each parallel. Male S5 (
Fig. 38B
) with dense and light erect setal patches. Male S6 (
Fig. 38B
) medially emarginate and slightly filled by transparent integument from which long setae arise. Male S7 (
Fig. 66B
) with setae fully banding S7 around midpoint of length; widening from midpoint to tip, apical half widest clearly before rounded lateral tips; apical half vaguely ovular, rim rounded outward, with slight medial bump. Male S8 (
Fig. 71B
) lateral projections distinct; medial projection nearly parallel-sided, apically emarginate. Male genital capsule (
Fig. 76B
) with outer corners, where gonocoxite tips curve inward, marked by obvious flange of about 90 degrees or greater, best seen in profile; from corner to apex, in profile, gonocoxite with low secondary bump but relatively unmodified overall; tip, in profile, pointed and abruptly bent ventrally; gonostylus tip position slightly exceeding that of gonocoxite, measured from above along primary axis of latter. Pubescence: See 
Fig. 56B
. Appears medium to dark gray overall, often somewhat brownish. Setae generally somewhat tan dorsally except on metasoma, whiter there and elsewhere toward venter, except as follows: leg inner faces orange; tergal basal zones dark.

